      "text": "Scenario: “AtlasCrawler” for a Search Engine\n\nBackground\n\nYour search engine’s ranking and retrieval quality depends on:\n        •        Fresh, high-quality documents\n        •        Coverage of priority domains\n        •        Stable, polite crawling (don’t overload sites)\n        •        Controlling recrawl frequency (avoid wasting scarce compute)\n\nYou have exactly 1,000 VMs available for all crawler execution (fetching + parsing). Storage and managed databases exist, but budget and operational simplicity still\nmatter.\n\nInputs\n\nYou are given:\n        •        Multiple seed URL lists (e.g., news, government, docs, forums). Seeds are continuously updated by internal teams.\n        •        A domain priority policy, where some domains and domain groups must be crawled more aggressively than others.\n\nHard requirements\n        1.        Multiple seeds: Must support ingesting many seed sources concurrently (with different priorities and trust levels).\n        2.        VM scarcity: System must cap and schedule work across 1,000 VMs, maximizing usefulness to search.\n        3.        No duplicate recrawls inside a window: A single canonical URL must not be rescanned more than once inside its configured “priority window.”\n        •        Example: if nytimes.com/... has a 10-minute window, don’t crawl it again within 10 minutes even if it is re-discovered.\n        4.        Domain priority: Some domains have higher priority than others; priority should affect both crawl scheduling and resource allocation.\n        5.        Search-engine benefit: The crawler must produce outputs usable by search: content, metadata, link graph signals, and fetch diagnostics.\n\nExplicit constraints\n        •        Internet is adversarial/unreliable: timeouts, redirects, traps, infinite calendars, duplicate content, near-duplicates.\n        •        Politeness constraints are expected (robots, per-host rate limits), but you must decide how far you go in this 45-minute design.\n        •        Multi-region is optional unless you think it’s required; but you must be explicit if you assume single-region.",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Scenario: “AtlasCrawler” for a Search Engine\n\nBackground\n\nYour search engine’s ranking and retrieval quality depends on:\n        •        Fresh, high-quality documents\n        •        Coverage of priority domains\n        •        Stable, polite crawling (don’t overload sites)\n        •        Controlling recrawl frequency (avoid wasting scarce compute)\n\nYou have exactly 1,000 VMs available for all crawler execution (fetching + parsing). Storage and managed databases exist, but budget and operational simplicity still matter.\n\nInputs\n\nYou are given:\n        •        Multiple seed URL lists (e.g., news, government, docs, forums). Seeds are continuously updated by internal teams.\n        •        A domain priority policy, where some domains and domain groups must be crawled more aggressively than others.\n\nHard requirements\n        1.        Multiple seeds: Must support ingesting many seed sources concurrently (with different priorities and trust levels).\n        2.        VM scarcity: System must cap and schedule work across 1,000 VMs, maximizing usefulness to search.\n        3.        No duplicate recrawls inside a window: A single canonical URL must not be rescanned more than once inside its configured “priority window.”\n        •        Example: if nytimes.com/... has a 10-minute window, don’t crawl it again within 10 minutes even if it is re-discovered.\n        4.        Domain priority: Some domains have higher priority than others; priority should affect both crawl scheduling and resource allocation.\n        5.        Search-engine benefit: The crawler must produce outputs usable by search: content, metadata, link graph signals, and fetch diagnostics.\n\nExplicit constraints\n        •        Internet is adversarial/unreliable: timeouts, redirects, traps, infinite calendars, duplicate content, near-duplicates.\n        •        Politeness constraints are expected (robots, per-host rate limits), but you must decide how far you go in this 45-minute design.\n        •        Multi-region is optional unless you think it’s required; but you must be explicit if you assume single-region.",
